Task 1: Set up BeEF for Browser Exploitation
Subtask 1.1: Install BeEF Framework
First, we need to install BeEF and its dependencies on our Linux system.

# Update the system packages
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install required dependencies
sudo apt install -y git ruby ruby-dev bundler sqlite3 libsqlite3-dev

# Clone the BeEF repository
cd /opt
sudo git clone https://github.com/beefproject/beef.git

# Change ownership to current user
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /opt/beef

# Navigate to BeEF directory
cd /opt/beef

# Install Ruby gems
bundle install
Subtask 1.2: Configure BeEF Settings
Now we'll configure BeEF with appropriate settings for our lab environment.

# Copy the default configuration file
cp config.yaml.example config.yaml

# Edit the configuration file
nano config.yaml
Modify the following sections in the configuration file:

beef:
    version: '0.5.4.0'
    debug: false
    crypto_default_value_length: 80
    
    restrictions:
        permitted_hooking_subnet: ["0.0.0.0/0"]
        permitted_ui_subnet: ["0.0.0.0/0"]
        
    credentials:
        user: "beef"
        passwd: "beef123"
        
    http:
        debug: false
        host: "0.0.0.0"
        port: "3000"
        
    https:
        enable: false
        
    database:
        driver: "sqlite"
        db_file: "beef.db"
Subtask 1.3: Start BeEF Framework
Launch BeEF and verify it's running correctly.

# Start BeEF
cd /opt/beef
./beef
You should see output similar to:

